In a range of input flux — depending of the valves’ sensitivity to the pressure gradient and permeability — valves can both open when closed and close back when open. In this flux range, activity is permanent and variable.
Within the domain of flux allowing permanent activity, different regimes can be observed:
Low flux, valves are mostly closed, and open in bursts: activity is low and time-clustered
Intermediary flux, valves open and close rapidly, randomly but at a constant rate: activity is high and Poisson-like
High flux, valves are mostly open, and when they close large bursts occur as they impede the flow: activity is low, and quasi-periodic
